Executes phase 2 of the lifecycle: starts an API proxy (in billed modes only), execs the cage via `bwrap` with that proxy mounted, and stops the proxy on cage exit. Returns the cage's exit code and an optional proxy diagnostic log.

The proxy runs in a dedicated thread with an `AtomicBool` stop flag; `run_until_exit` signals it after `bwrap` exits, then joins the thread and reads the proxy log from disk before teardown destroys the run dir. A proxy dial failure never fails the session itself (ADR-027) — diagnostics are best-effort context only.

In billed modes, the cage sees a relay (socat, port 8080) that forwards to a Unix socket bound by the proxy thread. The relay startup has a synchronous wait (polling `/proc/net/tcp`) to prevent ECONNREFUSED windows in Claude's own retry UI. The wait is a shell snippet parameterized by port so tests can avoid racing the host's 8080.

`run_until_exit(r: &Resolved, prep: &Prep) -> Result<RunOutcome, CageError>` is the entry point; it coordinates proxy lifecycle and calls `exec_cage` to spawn bwrap. `start_proxy` binds the Unix listener and spawns the accept loop; `exec_cage` builds the bwrap config and either runs on a PTY (interactive mode) or spawns bwrap directly. `cage_cmd_for_mode` returns per-mode shell commands: `SelfTestStub` runs containment proofs (writable workspace, secrets masked, git usable, no network), `Task` and `Interactive` both run claude via a relay + preflight sequence.

Auth is passthrough — no API key is injected; the caged claude's own OAuth header travels through.